{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/why-is-boosting-fitting-residual-9ac6f4e77550", "time": 1683000482.759079, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/why-is-boosting-fitting-residual-9ac6f4e77550/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Why is Boosting Fitting Residual. Generic Explanation for Boosting\u2026 | by Sun Weiran | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Why is Boosting Fitting Residual", "description": "Without much introduction, most data scientists should have experience using various boosting models, i.e. XGBoost, for projects or Kaggle competitions. Many articles describe boosting algorithm as\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Schapire", "anchor_text": "Schapire", "paragraph_index": 8}], "all_paragraphs": ["Boosting algorithm searches for the optimal weak learner functions that minimize loss function over the training data at every iteration. Every new learner will try to \u2018correct\u2019 errors made by previous learners.", "Without much introduction, most data scientists should have experience using various boosting models, i.e. XGBoost, for projects or Kaggle competitions. Many articles describe boosting algorithm as \u201crecursively adding weak learners to fit residual made by previous learners\u201d. Well, it\u2019s true, but why? This article aims to explain the concept of boosting in broader sense.", "Boosting or Forward Stagewise Additive Modeling is an ensemble learning method that combines many weak learners to form a collection that acts like a strong learner. It can generically described as follow.", "Before explain every steps in detail, let\u2019s clarify the symbols.", "Now let\u2019s take a look at each step.", "The most important step is 2a, which searches for the optimal weak learner function to add to the collection. When squared error is chosen as loss function, formula in 2a can be rewritten as:", "In this expression, f\u2098\u208b\u2081 represents predicted value from the previous trees. y\u1d62 represents actual value. y\u1d62 - f\u2098\u208b\u2081 will output residual from the previous learners, r\u1d62\u2098. Thus, to minimize the square losses, every new weak learner will fit the residual.", "For other common loss functions for regression problems, for example, absolute error and Huber loss, this statement still holds as residual is always computed.", "For a 2-class classification problem, AdaBoost, a famous boosting algorithm introduced by Freund and Schapire in 1997, uses exponential loss. At every iteration, training samples will be re-weighted based on prediction errors made by previous trees. Incorrectly classified samples will be given higher weight. Subsequent tree will fit the re-weighted training sample. Although new tree does not fit on the prediction error or the deviation directly, prediction error plays an important part in fitting new trees.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F9ac6f4e77550&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fwhy-is-boosting-fitting-residual-9ac6f4e77550&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fwhy-is-boosting-fitting-residual-9ac6f4e77550&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&sour